Kamal Feedback:

I was able to extract the code and review it.  Since Moieen did not provide the output with the module, I used the old output as reference and did notice that he correct whatever problem there was in the first submission.  The results are all correct and the code did catch all the error conditions.

Overall, the code is structure procedurally and functionally but is top-down which does indicate that Moieen is a Junior developer.  Much of the code is redundant and if more advanced features of Java were used such as StringTokenizer, a lot of the code could have been eliminated reducing the output to probably half the size.  Just a matter of learning the core language and its features.

There is minimal use of Objects and no application of OOD which is fine as the solution can be delivered either way.  It would have been good to see some use of OOD especially if you wanted to impress.

Without an interview to assess other problem solving capabilities I would rate him as Junior developer.   During the Interview I provide some thinking problems so you may want to use this one as it is good indicator of his actual problem solving ability:

Given two Sorted Arrays, devise an algorithm to find the First common element in both arrays.
(5,7,9,12,22,22,50,75)  Any array with numbers will suffice – put on board or paper for him to see
(1,6,8,9,13,22,90)  In the second array, have at least two numbers which match numbers in the first array

The goal is to see how he solves the problem for the First common element.  Once done, ask him to revise to find the kth common element (keeping in mind the duplicates).  In the example arrays above, the first common number is 9, the second is 22 and the third is 22 …

Depending the algorithm used, you may then ask the interview whether he can create a more efficient algorithm – one that process in O(n) – single loop.  My guess is they’ll use multiple loops within in each other on the first pass which is O(n2).
